               <p>WILLIAM BRAY. I <rs id="t18301209-67-viclabel396" type="occupation">keep the <placeName id="t18301209-67-crimeloc397">White Swan public-house</placeName>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-67-crimeloc397" type="placeName" value="White Swan public-house"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-67-crimeloc397" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                     <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301209-67-off394 t18301209-67-crimeloc397"></join>
                  </rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301209-67-victim696 t18301209-67-viclabel396"></join>. On the 17th of November, between five and six o'clock in the evening, I went into the tap-room, and stood before the fire - there was no one in the house but my family; my wife was sitting by the parlour fire, suckling an infant - she heard the till rattle, and called to me; I went into the bar, and found the prisoner - I took him by the collar: he opened his hand, and had 1d. in it - he said he wanted a penny worth of beer; I looked at him, and saw he had something in his month, trying to swallow it - I took hold of his throat, and he dropped one shilling and a sixpence<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183012090041"></xptr>from his mouth; I sent for an officer - I missed one shilling and a sixpence from the till - he begged very hard to be let go; he said he had no parents, and did it through distress.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301209-67-person697">
                  LEWIS 
                  LAROCHE
               <interp inst="t18301209-67-person697" type="surname" value="LAROCHE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-67-person697" type="given" value="LEWIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-67-person697" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was sent for, and took the prisoner- I have the shilling and sixpence; he said it was through distress, and he wished to be sent to the Refuge.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 14. - <rs id="t18301209-67-verdict398" type="verdictDescription">
